<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-448-688  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 448 688.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  July 1989 p24(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fine-tuned performance. (Vauxhall Motors Ltd.'s automatedautomobile production; includes related article on Vauxhall'sLuton, UK plant)</TITLE><AUTHOR>White, Kevin H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Vauxhall Motors' 90 million pound sterling automated paint plantuses Electronic Data Systems' automatic vehicle identification(AVI) system to control a 16-stage robotized spray paintingprocess for Cavalier auto bodies.andP;  AVI uses programmable markerson the bodies that transmit signals across a broadbandcommunications network to twin VAX 112/785s.andP;  The location of eachcar is constantly monitored.andP;  Any fault discovered in the paintingprocess is entered into a shop floor workstation using bar-codesand the defective car is rerouted to correct the problemimmediately.andP;  Another Vauxhall plant uses automated guidedvehicles (AGVs) to feed parts to assembly line workers along aoptimized process route determined by computer simulationsoftware.andP;  The parts supply is tightly coordinated, requiring nocentral warehouse.andP;  Some parts suppliers can linked to Vauxhallover Istel's Edict electronic data interchange (EDI) network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Vauxhall Motors Ltd. (automation)Electronic Data Systems Corp. (products).andO;Topic:     Automobile IndustryAutomationQuality ControlManufacturingShop Floor Control.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>